  "prompt": "What makes mayonnaise a dairy product?",
  "response": "Mayonnaise is not actually a dairy product. It is a common misconception because of its creamy texture and frequent association with dairy-based products like cheese and yogurt in various dishes. Here's why mayonnaise is **not** dairy:\n\n1. **Ingredients**: Traditional mayonnaise is made from **egg yolk, oil, vinegar or lemon juice, and seasonings**. None of these ingredients are derived from milk or other dairy sources.\n\n2. **Definition of Dairy**: Dairy products are foods produced from the milk of mammals, such as cows, goats, or sheep. Since mayonnaise contains no milk or milk-derived ingredients, it does not qualify as a dairy product.\n\n3. **Use Case**: Mayonnaise is often used as a condiment in place of or alongside dairy-based spreads like butter or cream cheese, which may contribute to the confusion.\n\nHowever, some commercially prepared mayonnaise products may contain **milk derivatives** (like whey or casein) as stabilizers or flavor enhancers, so it's always a good idea to check the label if you're avoiding dairy.",
